Ānandavratam — in honour of Brahmā. 
M. 101. 32.

आनर्त
Ānarta (I) (c) — a western country; that of Kṛṣṇa;1 on 
the way from Dvāraka to Indraprastha.2 Its king went to 
Syamantapañcaka for solar eclipse.3 Destroyed by Dvivida;4 
named after Śaryāti; its capital Kuśasthalī.5 1) Bhā. I. 11. 1.
 2) Ib. X. 71. 21.
 3) Ib. X. 82. 13; Br. II. 16. 
62; M. 12. 22.
 4) Ib. X. 67. 4.
 5) Vā. 86. 24; Vi. IV. 1. 64.


आनर्त
Ānarta (II) — a son of Śaryāti and father of Reva(ta).1 
Rocamāna was his son; ruled over the kingdom of Ānarta 
from Kuśasthalī.2 1) Bhā. IX. 3. 27; Br. III. 61. 18; Vā. 86. 23-24; Vi. IV. 1. 
63-4.
 2) M. 12. 21-2.


आनर्त
Ānarta (III) — a son of Vītihotra. 
M. 43. 49.

आनर्त
Ānartas — people of Ānarta over whom Revata ruled.1 
Heard of Kṛṣṇa going to Mithilā and met him on the way 
with presents;2 of the south.3 1) Bhā. I. 10, 35; 14. 25; IX. 3. 28; X. 52. 15; M. 114. 51.
 2) Bhā. X. 86. 20.
 3) Vā. 45. 131.


आनर्तपुरी
Ānartapurī — the capital of Ānarta — Dvāraka; from here 
Kṛṣṇa went to Vidarbha in one night. 
Bhā. I. 14. 25; X. 53. 6.

आन्त्यायन
Āntyāyana — a son of Bhṛgu, and a deva. 
Br. III. 1. 89.

आन्दोलिकनियुद्धम्
Āndolika-niyuddham — swinging on the hands of friends 
and boxing; by Kṛṣṇa and Rāma. 
Vi. V. 9. 8.

आन्धक
Āndhaka — a son of Vipracitti and Simhikā. 
Vi. I. 21. 12.

आन्धकार
Āndhakāra (c) — a kingdom after the name of Andha
kāra,1 near Pīvara hill.2 1) Br. II. 14. 25.
 2) Ib. II. 19. 72.


आन्ध्र
Āndhras (I) — the kings of Andhra dynasty, thirty in 
number, ruled the earth for 456 years. Seven of them were 
contemporaries of seven Kauśalas, chiefs of Vidūra and Niṣa
dhas;1 According to Matsya Purāṇa, 19 members of the 
dynasty ruled for 460 years. Kingdoms of Ārya and 
Mleccha existed side by side — Ābhīras, Gardabhilas, Śakas, 
Yavanas, Tuṣāras, Guruṇḍas, and Hūṇas.2 1) Bhā. XII. 1. 22-28 and 35.
 2) M. 272. 37; 273. 16-19, 25.


आन्ध्र
Āndhras (II) — a tribe purified by the worship of Hari.1 
Enlisted by Jarāsandha against the Yadus;2 a southern 
country unfit for performing Śrāddha.3 1) Bhā. II. 4. 18.
 2) Bhā. X. [50 (V) 3].
 3) Br. II. 16. 59; III. 
14. 80; IV. 29. 131.


आन्ध्रभृत्य
Āndhrabhṛtyas — seven in number. 
Vi. IV. 24. 51.

आनृहवान्
Ānṛhavān — a rājaṛṣi becoming a Brāhmaṇa. 
Vā. 91. 116.

आन्वीक्षिकि
Ānvīkṣiki (Adhyātmakī vidyā, s.v.) — Taught by Dat
tātreya to Alarka and others.1 Produced by Brahmā.2 
Helps concentration on the Absolute.3 Learnt by Rāma and 
Kṛṣṇa.4 Symbolical of Devī.5 1) Bhā. I. 3. 11; M. 215. 54; Vi. V. 10. 27.
 2) Bhā. III. 12. 44; 
25. 4.
 3) Ib. XI. 20. 24.
 4) Ib. X. 45. 34.
 5) Vi. I. 9. 121.


आह्निकक्रम
Āhnikakrama — the daily routine of duties. 
Vā. 53. 39; Vi. V. 18. 34.

आप
Āpa (I) — a vyāpaka. ety. of; came out of Agni, when 
the latter was lost in the earth. 
Br. I. 5. 131-5; II. 6. 56-7; 20. 1 and 5; Vā. 6. 1.

आप
Āpa (II) — a Rākṣasa with the Śarat sun. 
Br. II. 23. 15; Vā. 52. 15.

आप
Āpa (III) — a son of Vasiṣṭha, and a Prajāpati of the 
Svārociṣa epoch. 
M. 9. 9.

आप
Āpa (IV) — is Bhava; hence do not commit nuisance 
in waters; nor bathe naked, nor have sexual intercourse in 
water; forsake colourless, tasteless and small waters; their 
source is the ocean and hence they must not be stopped in 
their progress to it. 
Vā. 27. 21-7.

आपक
Āpakas — certain grahas which cause fear to children. 
Vā. 69. 191.

आपन
Āpana (c) — a kingdom to which Puramjana went by 
the entrance Mukhyā; allegorically Vyavahāra. 
Bhā. IV. 25. 49; 29. 12.

आपनाप
Āpanāpa — a pupil of Bāṣkali. 
Br. II. 35. 6.

आपव
Āpava (Vasiṣṭha) (I) — a sage of the time of second 
Sāvarṇa Manu.1 Finding his hermit destroyed by Kārta
vīrya's fire, cursed that he would be slain by Paraśurāma.2 
Resident of Hematālavanam.3 1) Br. IV. 1. 70.
 2) Ib. III. 69. 44-5; M. 44. 1. 12-14.
 3) M. 43. 41.


आपव
Āpava (II) — the son of Varuṇa; cursed Kārtavīryārjuna 
who allowed his tapovana to be consumed by Citrabhānu; 
for ages past he was performing penance at the place, living 
on water. 
Vā. 94. 43; 95. 11-13.

आपवत्स
Āpavatsa — to be worshipped in housebuildings. 
M. 253. 31; 268. 20.

आपस्तम्ब
Āpastamba — acted as priest in the Putreṣṭi of Diti. 
M. 7. 33-4; 192. 60.

आपस्तम्बि
Āpastambi — a Bhārgava, of Āṅgirasapravara. 
M. 195. 33; 196. 18.

आपस्थूण
Āpasthūṇas — Ekārṣeyas. 
M. 200. 4.

आपादबद्ध
Āpādabaddha — the son of Śātakarṇi, ruled for 30 years. 
Vā. 99. 351.

आपानगोष्ठि
Āpānagoṣṭhi — Revelry and mirth in the assembly of 
Kṛṣṇa with 16000 ladies; of Apsaras with Gandharvas. 
M. 70. 4; 120. 31.

आपिकायनि
Āpikāyani — ārṣeyapravara (Bhārgavas). 
M. 195. 41.

आपीतक
Āpītaka — son of Lambodara Āndhra, ruled for 12 years. 
M. 273. 5.

आपीशि
Āpīśi — ārṣeyapravara (Bhārgavas). 
M. 195. 41.

आपूरण
Āpūraṇa (I) — the Yakṣa who resides in the sun's 
chariot during the month of Bhādrapada. 
Vi. II. 10. 10.

आपूरण
Āpūraṇa (II) — a Nāga (Dhṛtarāṣṭra). 
Vā. 69. 72; Vi. IV. 8. 45.

आपोमयदेव
Āpomayadeva — worshipped in Krauñcadvīpa. 
Bhā. V. 20. 22-3.

आपोमूर्ति
Āpomūrti — an Ātreya; a sage of the epoch of the second 
Sāvarṇa Manu. 
Br. II. 11. 23; IV. 1. 70; Vā. 28. 20.

आपोलव
Āpolava — the son of Śāntakarṇi; ruled for 12 years. 
Br. III. 74. 163.

आप्तोर्याम
Āptoryāma — a sacrifice1 created from the west face of 
Brahmā.2 (north face-Vi. P.). 1) Bhā. III. 12. 40.
 2) Vi. I. 5. 56.


आप्नुवान
Āpnuvāna — a son of Bhṛgu and a gotrakara; a pravara 
of Bhārgava gotra; Father of Aurva. 
M. 195. 15 and 29.

आप्य
Āpya (I) — a Vājin. 
Vā. 61. 25.

आप्य
Āpya (II) — a particular period of the day. 
Vā. 66. 40.

आप्य
Āpyas — one of the gaṇas of the eight gods of the Cāk
ṣuṣa epoch. 
Bhā. VIII. 5. 8; Vi. III. 1. 27.

आप्यायन
Āpyāyana — a territorial division of Śālmalidvīpa. 
Bhā. V. 20. 9.

आप्यायनम्
Āpyāyanam — a particular offering to Agni, Soma and 
Yama in the Śrāddha ritual. First to Pitṛs and then to 
Devas, as Pitṛs are Pūrvadevatas. 
M. 15. 32-41; 16. 33; 17. 58.

आप्रवान
Āpravāna — a son of Cyavana; married Ṛci, daughter of 
Nahuṣa: Father of Aurva, born from her thigh. 
Br. III. 1. 93-5.

आबाधविस्तर
Ābādhavistara — of the earth; one crore in every direc
tion from Meru as centre; also calculated in another way. 
Vā. 50. 69-70.

आब्रह्मस्तम्बपर्यन्तम्
Ābrahmastambaparyantam — from Brahmā to grass. 
Vā. 110. 21, 64.

आभिचार
Ābhicāra — Incantations done by Purohita and ministers 
for defeating the enemy — according to Bhaṇḍa;1 Brhaspati 
did this on behalf of Indra to vanquish Rāji's sons.2 1) Br. IV. 21. 97.
 2) Vi. IV. 9. 19.


आभिल
Ābhila — a mahāratha, and a commander of Bhaṇḍa's 
army. His riding vehicle was Simha. 
Br. IV. 29. 21-2.

आभीर
Ābhīra — country of Ābhīras.1 Dvijas of, became vrātyas 
after Puramjaya's days.2 Purified of sin by devotion to 
Hari.3 Seven of this tribe ruled from Avabhṛti.4 The 
Braḥmāṇḍa and Vāyu say ten of them ruled after the 
Āndhras;5 for 67 years. 1) Bhā. I. 10. 35; Br. II. 16. 46 and 57; 18. 48.
 2) Bhā. XII 
1. 38.
 3) Ib. II. 4. 18.
 4) Bhā. XII. 1. 29; Vā. 99. 359; Vi. IV. 
24. 51, 68.
 5) Br. III. 74. 174; M. 50. 76; 114. 40; 163. 72; 273. 18.


आभीर
Ābhīras — a tribe of Dakṣiṇāpatha saw Arjuna singly 
carrying much wealth and women and attacked him; he took 
up his Gāṇḍiva and found he had lost its secret and power;1 
freebooters and shepherds of the Pañcanada country who 
lived in villages; mlecchas; chief weapons of, staves and 
cudgels.2 1) Vā. 45. 115, 126; 47. 46; 99. 269; Vi. II. 3. 16.
 2) Vi. V. 
38. 14-28, 50-52.


आभीरकन्या
Ābhīrakanyā — observed the Kalyāṇinī vratam and 
became Urvaśī of the Heaven. 
M. 69. 59.

आभूतरजस
Ābhūtarajasa — gods of the Raivata epoch. 
M. 9. 20.

आभूतसम्प्लव
Ābhūtasamplava — or the Deluge; the duration of des
truction of all except the five bhūtas, earth, water, vāyu, 
ākāśa and tejas; eternal and not dying. 
Vā. 6. 74; 7, 22; 10. 33; 28. 16 and 32; 30. 318; 50. 206, 
212; 52. 47; 53. 76; 54. 109; 59. 57; 100. 11, 33, 37, 203, 240: 
101. 73, 334, 354; Vi. II. 8. 92-97: Br. II. 6. 22; IV. 1. 200 and 
208, 230-31, 242; M. 2. 16 and 20; 4. 20; 80. 11: 89. 10; 106. 
10; 124. 94 and 102; 128. 44; 181. 4; 188. 96; 192. 32; 204. 
10; 206. 40.

आभ्रहमु
Ābhrahamu — a son of Bhadra. 
Vā. 69. 213.

आम
Āma (I) — a son of Ghṛtapṛṣṭha. 
Bhā. V. 20. 21.

आम
Āma (II) — a son of Kṛṣṇa and (Satyā) daughter of 
Nagnacit. 
Bhā. X. 61. 13.

आमगर्भ
Āmagarbhas — Pitṛs dead as small children. 
Vā. 110. 53.

आमपात्रम्
Āmapātram — the milking vessel of the Yakṣas. 
Br. II. 36. 215; Vā. 62. 182.

आमश्राद्धम्
Āmaśrāddham — see Āmānnam. 
M. 18. 27; Vā. 18. 20.

आमान्नम्
Āmānnam — gift of uncooked food in a śrāddha, gene
rally by Śūdras; also Āmaśrāddham; forbidden for yatis. 
M. 17. 70; Vā. 18. 20.

आमोद
Āmoda — a vighna nāyaka. 
Br. IV. 27. 81; 44. 68.

आम्नायनाथा
Āmnāyanāthā — a name of Lalitā. 
Br. IV. 18. 17.

आम्ब
Āmba — a son of Kṛṣṇa. 
Bhā. I. 10. 29.

आम्बिकेय
Āmbikeya (I) — a place where Hiraṇyākṣa was slain by 
Vārāha Hari. 
M. 122. 16.

आम्बिकेय
Āmbikeya (II) — a hill of the Śākadvīpam. 
Vā. 49. 84; Vi. II. 4. 62.

आम्र
Āmra — the mango tree in Brahmasaras, in the shape 
of Brahmā; he who waters the tree will lead the Pitṛs to 
salvation. 
Vā. 43. 6; 111. 35-36.

आम्रवनम्
Āmravanam — between Viśākha and Pataṅga hills. 
Vā. 38. 18-22.

आम्रातकेश्वरम्
Āmrātakeśvaram — a tīrtham on the Narmadā sacred 
to Pitṛs, and to Śiva. 
M. 22. 51; 181. 28; 190. 5.

आय
Āya — a Tuṣita god. 
Br. II. 36. 11.

आयतनम्
Āyatanam of Deva — called divyam by the Veda, at the 
end of Nirāloka and of ākāśa or ether: Inaccessible to gods.1 
Temples as places for śrāddha; construction of: description 
shows the Vaiṣṇava and Śaiva shrines in the same com
pound.2 Shrines where Purāṇas were read.3 1) Br. II. 19. 168-9; III. 11. 34.
 2) M. 17. 11; 58. 2; 83. 3; 
105. 15; 268. 35; 270. 34.
 3) Vā. 4. 7; 30. 150; 38. 31, 48, 58; 54. 3; 
77. 63; 92. 52.


आयतायन
Āyatāyana — A Trayārṣeya. 
M. 198. 3.

आयति
Āyati (I) — a daughter of Meru and Dharaṇi, wife of 
Dhātṛ (Vidhātṛ-Vā. P.) and mother of Mṛkaṇḍa;1 mother of 
Prāṇa also.2 1) Bhā. IV. 1. 43-44; Vā. 28. 4; 30. 34; Vi. I. 10. 3.
 2) Br. II. 
11. 5-6; 13. 37.


आयति
Āyati (II) — a son of Nahuṣa. 
Bhā. IX. 18. 1; Br. III. 68. 12; Vā. 93. 13; Vi. IV. 10. 1.

आयसम्पात्रम्
Āyasampātram — the iron vessel sacred to Asuras. 
Br. II. 36. 210; M. 10. 20.

आयाप्य
Āyāpya — a mantrakṛt and of Aṅgirasa branch. 
Vā. 59. 101.

आयु
Āyu (I) — a son of Prāṇa and Ūrjasvatī: a Vasu;1 Father 
of Vaitaṇḍya and others.2 1) Bhā. VI. 6. 12.
 2) Br. III. 3. 21, 24.


आयु
Āyu (II) — the son of Puruhotra, and father of Sātvata. 
Bhā. IX. 24. 6.

आयु
Āyu (III) — one of the six sons of Purūravas and Urvaśī; 
wife Prabhā, Rāhu's daughter; father of five sons, Nahuṣa, 
Vṛddhaśarman, Rāju, Dambha, and Vipāpman, all of them 
expert warriors. 
Bhā. IX. 15. 1; 17. 1; Br. III. 66. 22, 90; 67. 1; M. 24. 33-5; 
Vā. 91. 51; Vi. IV. 6. 73; 7. 1; 8. 1-3.

आयु
Āyu (IV) — a son of Kṛṣṇa and Bhadrā. 
Bhā. X. 61. 17.

आयु
Āyu (V) — The sage presiding over the month of Puṣya. 
Bhā. XII. 11. 42.

आयु
Āyu (VI) — (Śuci Agni). Father of Mahiṣa. 
Br. II. 12. 38-40.

आयु
Āyu (VII) — a Carakādhvaryu. 
Br. II. 33. 13.

आयु
Āyu (VIII) — the Agni that lives in Paśu. 
Vā. 29. 37.

आयु
Āyu (IX) — a son of Aṅgirasa; father of Amāvasu. 
Vā. 65. 105; 73. 5.

आयुतायु
Āyutāyu — the son of Sindhudvīpa. 
M. 12. 46; Vā. 88. 173.

आयुध
Āyudhas — weapons of war, enumerated and described. 
Br. IV. 22. 10-14; M. 129. 35; 149. 7-8; 173. 5, 12, 29, etc.

आयुधागार
Āyudhāgāra — arsenal: meddling with it was punished 
with death. 
M. 163. 51; 215. 44; 217. 16; 227. 174.

आयुर्दा
Āyurdā — R. in Śākadvīpa. 
Bhā. V. 20. 26.

आयुर्दान
Āyurdāna — a Pārāvata god. 
Br. II. 36. 14.

आयुर्वेद
Āyurveda — originated from Dhanvantari;1 from the 
east face of Brahmā;2 one of the eighteen vidyas;3 begins in 
Dvāpara;4 Bharadvāja was the compiler of the Āyurveda and 
other sciences connected with medicine; it was divided into 
eight parts each of which was given to one of his disciples.5 1) Bhā. II. 7. 21; VIII. 8. 35; IX. 17. 4; Br. III. 67. 18; Vā. 92. 
16; Vi. IV. 8. 10.
 2) Bhā. III. 12. 38.
 3) Br. II. 35. 88; Vi. III. 6. 28; 
Vā. 61. 79.
 4) M. 144. 22; Vā. 58. 23; Br. II. 31. 23.
 5) Vā. 92. 
22; Br. III. 67. 24.


आयुर्व्रतम्
Āyurvratam — in honour of Śiva. 
M. 101. 22.

आयुष
Āyuṣa — the son of Aiḍa. 
Vā. 1. 192.

आयुष्मत्
Āyuṣmat (I) — the father of Ṛṣabha-Hari by Ambu
dhārā. 
Bhā. VIII. 13. 20.

आयुष्मत्
Āyuṣmat (II) — a son of Uttānapāda. 
Br. II. 36. 89.

आयुष्मत्
Āyuṣmat (III) — a son of Praḥlāda. 
M. 6. 9; Vi. I. 21. 1.

आयुष्मत्य
Āyuṣmatya — an apsarasa gaṇa from Sūrya. 
Vā. 69. 55.

आयुष्मन्त
Āyuṣmanta — a gaṇa of gods. 
Br. IV. 1. 122.

आरट्टदेश
Āraṭṭadeśa — noted for horses. 
M. 48. 7.

आरण्य
Āraṇya — a madhyamādhvaryu; a Prajāpati and father 
of five deva gaṇas of the Cākṣuṣa epoch.1 Son of Atri.2 1) Br. II. 33. 15; 36. 68.
 2) Vā. 62. 58.


आरण्यवाक्य
Āraṇyavākyas — passages of the Āraṇyaka portion of the 
Vedas. 
Br. III. 21. 55.

आरब्ध
Ārabdha — the son of Setu and father of Gāndhāra. 
Bhā. IX. 23. 15; Vi. IV. 17. 3-4.

आरम्भयज्ञ
Ārambhayajñas — for Kṣatriyas. 
Br. II. 29. 55; Vā. 57. 50.

आराधि
Ārādhi — a son of Jayatsena. 
Vā. 99. 231.

आराधित
Ārādhita — a son of Jayatsena and father of Ayutāyu. 
Vi. IV. 20. 4.

आराम
Ārāma — Laying out parks at the auspicious hour — also 
Udyāna;1 in Tripuram;2 punishment for misuse of.3 1) M. 58. 1 and 52.
 2) Ib. 130. 5.
 3) Ib. 227. 30; Vā. 101. 160.


आरुणायनि
Āruṇāyani — ārṣeya pravara (Aṅgiras). 
M. 196. 8.

आरुणि
Āruṇi (I) — a siddha. 
Bhā. VI. 15. 13.

आरुणि
Āruṇi (II) — (Ātreya) a sage of the epoch of the third 
Sāvarṇa Manu. 
Br. IV. 1. 79.

आरुणि
Āruṇi (III) — a sādhya. 
M. 171. 43.

आरुणि
Āruṇi (IV) — the fifteenth Vyāsa, Vedaśiras, the avatār 
of the Lord. 
Vā. 23. 166.

आरुणि
Āruṇi (V) — a sage of the XIth epoch of Manu. 
Vi. III. 2. 31.

आरुणि
Āruṇi (VI) — the first of the madhyadeśas. 
Vā. 61. 9.

आर्चनानश
Ārcanānaśa — an Ātreya gotrakāra. 
M. 197. 5.

आर्जव
Ārjava — a pupil of Bāṣkali. 
Br. II. 35. 6.

आर्तव
Ārtavas (I) — five sons of Brahmā: represented by 
Agniṣvāttas. 
Br. II. 21. 152; 23. 75-77; 28. 16 ff.

आर्तव
Ārtavas (II) — five sons of Ṛtus: These are half months: 
Represent Pitṛs;1 sections of the year; depend on the seasons.2 1) M. 141. 14 and 57; Vā. 30. 18, 22.
 2) Vā. 70. 14; Br. II. 
13. 19-25, 149.


आर्द्रक
Ārdraka — the father of Dhṛti. 
Br. III. 71. 124.

आर्द्रा
Ārdrā — the name of a constellation. 
Vā. 82. 3.

आर्द्रानन्दकरि
Ārdrānandakari — Tṛtīyāvratam: sacred to Bhavānī sit
ting with Mahādeva: to be done for four months, once in 
every pakṣa: the performer enjoys the world of Rudrāṇī. 
M. 64 (whole).

आर्य
Ārya (I) — opposite of Mleccha. 
Vā. 45. 93; 47. 49; 99. 404.

आर्य
Ārya (II) — collective name of Aṅgiras' sons1 as oppo
sed to Mleccha.2 Their country was Bhāratavarṣa; side by 
side with Mleccha in Kaliyuga.3 1) Bhā. IX. 4. 2; Br. II. 16. 24.
 2) M. 227. 198; 114. 20.
 3) M. 121. 46-51; 273. 25; 274. 37.


आर्यक
Āryaka (I) — the father of Dharmasetu. 
Bhā. VIII. 13. 26.

आर्यक
Āryaka (II) — a Kādraveya nāga. 
Br. III. 7. 33.

आर्यक
Āryakas — caste equal to Brāhmaṇa in Plakṣadvīpa. 
Vi. II. 4. 17.

आर्यका
