Br. IV. 29. 122.
 7) Vi. IV. 15. 1-15.


शिशुमार
Śiśumāra (I) — a Prajāpati; father of Bhrami and 
father-in-law of Dhruva. 
Bhā. IV. 10. 11.

शिशुमार
Śiśumāra (II) — the form of the system of heavenly 
bodies supposed to be yoga power of Hari. At the end of the 
tail is Dhruva and on the tail are other gods like Indra, Agni, 
Kaśyapa; on its back lies the Ajavīthi and on the stomach 
the Ganges. Similarly all constellations and planets are 
seen on the different limbs of its body;1 described.2 1) Bhā. II. 2. 24; V. 23. 4-8; VI. 6. 14; Br. I. 1. 85. II. 23. 99; 
M. 125. 5-9; 127. 19; Vā. 1. 101; Vi. II. 12. 29, 34.
 2) M. 128. 19-25.


शिशुमार
Śiśumāra (III) — is Tārāmaya; the eternal deity; Uttā
napāda is the upper jaw, Yajña is the lower lip, Dharma is 
the head, heart is Nārāyaṇa, Sādhya and Aśvins front feet, 
Varuṇa and Aryama is the hind feet, the samvatsara, child; 
Mitra is Apāna; tail is Agni, Mahendra, Marīci and Kaśyapa 
and Dhruva; all the planets are centred in Dhruva. 
Vā. 52. 90-9; Vi. II. 9. 23-4.

शिशुमारपुर
Śiśumārapura — in the third tala or Vitala. 
Vā. 50. 26.

शिशुमार्ग
Śiśumārga — an Asura with a city in the third Talam. 
